{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848308605,"sessionID":"ses_28731db20ffeapDDhzVx7gaQDp","part":{"id":"prt_d78cebabf0014mFiSeR8yV7lwS","messageID":"msg_d78ceaf08001ZA1nZc2sHuGq2v","sessionID":"ses_28731db20ffeapDDhzVx7gaQDp","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_3d254cf2cc444378858a99e1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Spec: AR-009 — Router HTTP 反向代理核心\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: This delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing the HTTP reverse proxy core in `pkg/router`.\n6: \n7: ## Base Specifications\n8: \n9: - **AR**: AR-009\n10: - **Module**: `pkg/router`\n11: - **Language**: Go\n12: - **Size**: M\n13: \n14: ---\n15: \n16: ## Background\n17: \n18: The router module is responsible for routing HTTP requests to backend Sandbox services dynamically discovered from AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs. This delta implements the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## Requirement: Router Configuration\n23: \n24: ### Scenario: Router loads configuration with defaults\n25: \n26: **GIVEN** a Router instance is created with no explicit configuration\n27: **WHEN** the router starts\n28: **THEN** it SHOULD use default values: listen address `:8080`, backend timeout `30s`, idle timeout `60s`, health check interval `10s`\n29: \n30: ### Scenario: Router loads custom configuration\n31: \n32: **GIVEN** a Router instance is created with custom configuration\n33: **WHEN** the configuration specifies `listenAddress: \":9090\"`, `backendTimeout: \"60s\"`, `rateLimitEnabled: true`, `rateLimitRPS: 50`\n34: **THEN** the router SHOULD listen on port 9090, use 60s backend timeout, and enable rate limiting at 50 RPS\n35: \n36: ### Scenario: Router watches specific namespaces\n37: \n38: **GIVEN** a Router configured with `watchNamespaces: [\"ns1\", \"ns2\"]`\n39: **WHEN** the router starts its informers\n40: **THEN** it SHOULD only watch AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs in namespaces \"ns1\" and \"ns2\"\n41: \n42: ---\n43: \n44: ## Requirement: HTTP Server Lifecycle\n45: \n46: ### Scenario: Router starts HTTP server\n47: \n48: **GIVEN** a configured Router instance\n49: **WHEN** `Start()` is called\n50: **THEN** an HTTP server SHOULD start listening on the configured address\n51: **AND** the server SHOULD be ready to accept incoming requests\n52: \n53: ### Scenario: Router graceful shutdown\n54: \n55: **GIVEN** a running Router with active connections\n56: **WHEN** `Shutdown()` is called with a context\n57: **THEN** the server SHOULD stop accepting new connections\n58: **AND** it SHOULD wait for in-flight requests to complete within the context timeout\n59: **AND** it SHOULD close all idle connections\n60: \n61: ### Scenario: Router handles server startup error\n62: \n63: **GIVEN** a Router configured with an invalid address (e.g., unsupported port)\n64: **WHEN** `Start()` is called\n65: **THEN** it SHOULD return an error indicating the address is invalid or port is not accessible\n66: \n67: ---\n68: \n69: ## Requirement: Endpoint Discovery from AgentRuntime CR\n70: \n71: ### Scenario: Router discovers new AgentRuntime endpoint\n72: \n73: **GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime informer running\n74: **WHEN** a new AgentRuntime CR is created with `status.endpoint: \"http://10.0.0.1:8080\"` and `status.phase: Running`\n75: **THEN** the router SHOULD add the endpoint to its backend pool\n76: **AND** the endpoint SHOULD be available for routing\n77: \n78: ### Scenario: Router removes deleted AgentRuntime endpoint\n79: \n80: **GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime endpoint in its backend pool\n81: **WHEN** the corresponding AgentRuntime CR is deleted\n82: **THEN** the router SHOULD remove the endpoint from the backend pool\n83: **AND** no new requests SHOULD be routed to that endpoint\n84: \n85: ### Scenario: Router updates AgentRuntime endpoint on status change\n86: \n87: **GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime endpoint in its backend pool\n88: **WHEN** the AgentRuntime CR status is updated with a new endpoint address\n89: **THEN** the router SHOULD update the backend pool with the new endpoint\n90: **AND** existing connections to the old endpoint SHOULD be closed\n91: \n92: ### Scenario: Router ignores non-running AgentRuntime\n93: \n94: **GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime informer\n95: **WHEN** an AgentRuntime CR is created with `status.phase: Pending`\n96: **THEN** the router SHOULD NOT add the endpoint to the backend pool\n97: \n98: ---\n99: \n100: ## Requirement: Endpoint Discovery from CodeInterpreter CR\n101: \n102: ### Scenario: Router discovers new CodeInterpreter endpoint\n103: \n104: **GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter informer running\n105: **WHEN** a new CodeInterpreter CR is created with `status.endpoint: \"http://10.0.0.2:8080\"` and `status.phase: Running`\n106: **THEN** the router SHOULD add the endpoint to its backend pool\n107: \n108: ### Scenario: Router removes deleted CodeInterpreter endpoint\n109: \n110: **GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter endpoint in its backend pool\n111: **WHEN** the corresponding CodeInterpreter CR is deleted\n112: **THEN** the router SHOULD remove the endpoint from the backend pool\n113: \n114: ### Scenario: Router updates CodeInterpreter endpoint on status change\n115: \n116: **GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter endpoint in its backend pool\n117: **WHEN** the CodeInterpreter CR status is updated with a new endpoint address\n118: **THEN** the router SHOULD update the backend pool with the new endpoint\n119: \n120: ### Scenario: Router ignores non-running CodeInterpreter\n121: \n122: **GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter informer\n123: **WHEN** a CodeInterpreter CR is created with `status.phase: Failed`\n124: **THEN** the router SHOULD NOT add the endpoint to the backend pool\n125: \n126: ---\n127: \n128: ## Requirement: Path-Based Routing\n129: \n130: ### Scenario: Router routes request by path prefix\n131: \n132: **GIVEN** a backend pool containing endpoint \"http://backend-1:8080\" registered for path prefix `/agent/`\n133: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/agent/session-123`\n134: **THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://backend-1:8080/session-123`\n135: \n136: ### Scenario: Router routes request to code interpreter path\n137: \n138: **GIVEN** a backend pool containing endpoint \"http://ci-1:8080\" registered for path `/code/`\n139: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/code/execute`\n140: **THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://ci-1:8080/execute`\n141: \n142: ### Scenario: Router returns 404 for unmatched path\n143: \n144: **GIVEN** a router with configured routes\n145: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/unknown/path`\n146: **THEN** the router SHOULD return HTTP 404 response\n147: \n148: ### Scenario: Router handles path with query parameters\n149: \n150: **GIVEN** a backend pool containing endpoint \"http://backend:8080\" registered for path `/api/`\n151: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/api/data?param=value`\n152: **THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://backend:8080/data?param=value`\n153: \n154: ---\n155: \n156: ## Requirement: Header-Based Routing\n157: \n158: ### Scenario: Router routes request by custom header\n159: \n160: **GIVEN** a router configured with header-based routing rule: header `X-Backend` maps to corresponding backend\n161: **AND** a backend pool with endpoint \"http://backend-a:8080\" for header value \"backend-a\"\n162: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with header `X-Backend: backend-a`\n163: **THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://backend-a:8080`\n164: \n165: ### Scenario: Router routes request by content-type header\n166: \n167: **GIVEN** a router configured with header routing for `Content-Type`\n168: **AND** a backend pool with endpoint for JSON requests\n169: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with header `Content-Type: application/json`\n170: **THEN** the request SHOULD be routed to the appropriate backend\n171: \n172: ### Scenario: Router falls back to default when header not matched\n173: \n174: **GIVEN** a router configured with header-based routing and a default backend\n175: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with header `X-Custom: unknown-value`\n176: **AND** no backend is configured for \"unknown-value\"\n177: **THEN** the request SHOULD be routed to the default backend\n178: \n179: ---\n180: \n181: ## Requirement: Health Checking\n182: \n183: ### Scenario: Router performs periodic health checks\n184: \n185: **GIVEN** a backend pool with endpoints\n186: **WHEN** the health check interval (default 10s) elapses\n187: **THEN** the router SHOULD send health check requests to each backend\n188: **AND** mark backends as healthy or unhealthy based on the response\n189: \n190: ### Scenario: Router removes unhealthy backend from pool\n191: \n192: **GIVEN** a backend pool with a healthy endpoint\n193: **WHEN** the endpoint fails health checks for 3 consecutive attempts\n194: **THEN** the router SHOULD mark the backend as unhealthy\n195: **AND** stop routing requests to that backend\n196: \n197: ### Scenario: Router adds recovered backend back to pool\n198: \n199: **GIVEN** a backend pool with an unhealthy endpoint\n200: **WHEN** the endpoint passes a health check\n201: **THEN** the router SHOULD mark the backend as healthy\n202: **AND** resume routing requests to that backend\n203: \n204: ### Scenario: Health check timeout\n205: \n206: **GIVEN** a backend endpoint that does not respond\n207: **WHEN** a health check request times out (default 5s)\n208: **THEN** the backend SHOULD be marked as unhealthy\n209: \n210: ---\n211: \n212: ## Requirement: Connection Pooling\n213: \n214: ### Scenario: Router reuses connections to backends\n215: \n216: **GIVEN** a router with connection pooling enabled\n217: **WHEN** multiple requests are routed to the same backend\n218: **THEN** the router SHOULD reuse existing connections via HTTP keep-alive\n219: **AND** not create a new connection for each request\n220: \n221: ### Scenario: Router limits connections per backend\n222: \n223: **GIVEN** a router configured with `maxConnsPerBackend: 100`\n224: **WHEN** more than 100 concurrent connections exist to a backend\n225: **THEN** the router SHOULD queue additional connection requests\n226: **OR** return an error indicating the backend is overloaded\n227: \n228: ### Scenario: Router closes idle connections\n229: \n230: **GIVEN** a router with `idleTimeout: 60s`\n231: **WHEN** a connection to a backend has been idle for 60 seconds\n232: **THEN** the router SHOULD close the idle connection\n233: \n234: ---\n235: \n236: ## Requirement: Rate Limiting\n237: \n238: ### Scenario: Rate limiting restricts requests per client\n239: \n240: **GIVEN** a router with rate limiting enabled (`rateLimitRPS: 10`)\n241: **WHEN** a client sends 15 requests per second\n242: **THEN** the router SHOULD allow 10 requests through\n243: **AND** return HTTP 429 for the remaining 5 requests\n244: \n245: ### Scenario: Rate limiting uses token bucket algorithm\n246: \n247: **GIVEN** a router with rate limiting enabled\n248: **WHEN** requests arrive at varying rates\n249: **THEN** the router SHOULD use token bucket algorithm for smooth rate limiting\n250: **AND** allow burst traffic up to the bucket size\n251: \n252: ### Scenario: Rate limiting is disabled by default\n253: \n254: **GIVEN** a router with default configuration\n255: **WHEN** the router starts without explicit rate limit settings\n256: **THEN** rate limiting SHOULD NOT be active\n257: **AND** all requests SHOULD be processed normally\n258: \n259: ---\n260: \n261: ## Requirement: Authentication Middleware\n262: \n263: ### Scenario: Router validates authentication token\n264: \n265: **GIVEN** a router with authentication enabled\n266: **WHEN** a request arrives with valid `Authorization: Bearer <token>`\n267: **THEN** the request SHOULD be allowed through\n268: \n269: ### Scenario: Router rejects unauthenticated request\n270: \n271: **GIVEN** a router with authentication enabled\n272: **WHEN** a request arrives without `Authorization` header\n273: **THEN** the router SHOULD return HTTP 401 response\n274: \n275: ### Scenario: Router rejects invalid token\n276: \n277: **GIVEN** a router with authentication enabled\n278: **WHEN** a request arrives with invalid `Authorization: Bearer <invalid-token>`\n279: **THEN** the router SHOULD return HTTP 401 response\n280: \n281: ### Scenario: Authentication is disabled by default\n282: \n283: **GIVEN** a router with default configuration\n284: **WHEN** the router starts without explicit auth settings\n285: **AND** a request arrives without authorization\n286: **THEN** the request SHOULD be allowed through\n287: \n288: ---\n289: \n290: ## Requirement: Metrics\n291: \n292: ### Scenario: Router exposes request latency metric\n293: \n294: **GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n295: **WHEN** a request is proxied to a backend\n296: **THEN** a Prometheus histogram `router_request_duration_seconds` SHOULD be recorded\n297: \n298: ### Scenario: Router exposes backend request count metric\n299: \n300: **GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n301: **WHEN** requests are proxied to backends\n302: **THEN** a Prometheus counter `router_backend_requests_total` SHOULD be incremented per backend\n303: \n304: ### Scenario: Router exposes backend health status metric\n305: \n306: **GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n307: **WHEN** backend health status changes\n308: **THEN** a Prometheus gauge `router_backend_healthy` SHOULD reflect the status (1=healthy, 0=unhealthy)\n309: \n310: ### Scenario: Router exposes error rate metric\n311: \n312: **GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n313: **WHEN** a proxied request fails (backend error or timeout)\n314: **THEN** a Prometheus counter `router_errors_total` SHOULD be incremented\n315: \n316: ---\n317: \n318: ## Requirement: Request Logging\n319: \n320: ### Scenario: Router logs incoming requests\n321: \n322: **GIVEN** a router with logging middleware active\n323: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received\n324: **THEN** the log SHOULD contain: method, path, client IP, timestamp\n325: \n326: ### Scenario: Router logs proxied response status\n327: \n328: **GIVEN** a router with logging middleware active\n329: **WHEN** a proxied request completes\n330: **THEN** the log SHOULD contain: status code, response time, backend URL\n331: \n332: ---\n333: \n334: ## Acceptance Criteria\n335: \n336: - [ ] Router loads configuration with proper defaults\n337: - [ ] Router starts and listens on configured address\n338: - [ ] Router gracefully shuts down with active connections\n339: - [ ] Endpoints are discovered from AgentRuntime CRs with Running phase\n340: - [ ] Endpoints are removed when AgentRuntime CR is deleted\n341: - [ ] Endpoints are discovered from CodeInterpreter CRs with Running phase\n342: - [ ] Endpoints are removed when CodeInterpreter CR is deleted\n343: - [ ] Requests are routed based on path prefix\n344: - [ ] Requests are routed based on custom headers\n345: - [ ] 404 is returned for unmatched paths\n346: - [ ] Health checks run at configured intervals\n347: - [ ] Unhealthy backends are removed from routing pool\n348: - [ ] Healthy backends are restored after recovery\n349: - [ ] Connection pooling reuses HTTP connections\n350: - [ ] Connection limits per backend are enforced\n351: - [ ] Rate limiting restricts requests when enabled\n352: - [ ] Rate limiting allows requests when disabled\n353: - [ ] Authentication validates bearer tokens\n354: - [ ] Unauthenticated requests are rejected when auth enabled\n355: - [ ] Metrics are exported for Prometheus scraping\n356: - [ ] Request logs contain method, path, status, duration\n357: - [ ] Graceful shutdown completes within timeout\n\n(End of file - total 357 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Spec: AR-009 — Router HTTP 反向代理核心\n\n## Overview\n\nThis delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing the HTTP reverse proxy core in `pkg/router`.\n\n## Base Specifications\n\n- **AR**: AR-009\n- **Module**: `pkg/router`\n- **Language**: Go\n- **Size**: M\n\n---\n\n## Background\n\nThe router module is responsible for routing HTTP requests to backend Sandbox services dynamically discovered from AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs. This delta implements the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775848308594,"end":1775848308602}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775848308630,"sessionID":"ses_28731db20ffeapDDhzVx7gaQDp","part":{"id":"prt_d78cebf7c001S0Ykd3ZEZIDUvK","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d78ceaf08001ZA1nZc2sHuGq2v","sessionID":"ses_28731db20ffeapDDhzVx7gaQDp","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":22948,"input":592,"output":117,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":22239}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775848312394,"sessionID":"ses_28731db20ffeapDDhzVx7gaQDp","part":{"id":"prt_d78cece49001dDOSkrsh2agXNE","messageID":"msg_d78cebfa9001unsVDXOPSZUQ72","sessionID":"ses_28731db20ffeapDDhzVx7gaQDp","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848316339,"sessionID":"ses_28731db20ffeapDDhzVx7gaQDp","part":{"id":"prt_d78ceda6f001KnVrIuja2exagB","messageID":"msg_d78cebfa9001unsVDXOPSZUQ72","sessionID":"ses_28731db20ffeapDDhzVx7gaQDp","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_46d85371506b4f8b9bae87d4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/router/backend.go"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/router/backend.go</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: package router\n2: \n3: import (\n4: \t\"net/url\"\n5: \t\"sync\"\n6: \t\"time\"\n7: )\n8: \n9: type Backend struct {\n10: \tURL                 *url.URL\n11: \tPathPrefix          string\n12: \tName                string\n13: \tHealthy             bool\n14: \tConsecutiveFailures int\n15: \tLastHealthyCheck    time.Time\n16: \tmu                  sync.RWMutex\n17: }\n18: \n19: type BackendPool struct {\n20: \tbackends       map[string]*Backend\n21: \theaderRoutes   map[string]map[string]string // header name -> header value -> backend key\n22: \tdefaultBackend string\n23: \tmu             sync.RWMutex\n24: }\n25: \n26: func NewBackendPool() *BackendPool {\n27: \treturn &BackendPool{\n28: \t\tbackends:       make(map[string]*Backend),\n29: \t\theaderRoutes:   make(map[string]map[string]string),\n30: \t\tdefaultBackend: \"\",\n31: \t}\n32: }\n33: \n34: func (bp *BackendPool) AddBackend(key, endpoint, pathPrefix, name string) error {\n35: \tbp.mu.Lock()\n36: \tdefer bp.mu.Unlock()\n37: \n38: \tparsedURL, err := url.Parse(endpoint)\n39: \tif err != nil {\n40: \t\treturn err\n41: \t}\n42: \n43: \tbp.backends[key] = &Backend{\n44: \t\tURL:              parsedURL,\n45: \t\tPathPrefix:       pathPrefix,\n46: \t\tName:             name,\n47: \t\tHealthy:          true,\n48: \t\tLastHealthyCheck: time.Now(),\n49: \t}\n50: \n51: \tif bp.defaultBackend == \"\" {\n52: \t\tbp.defaultBackend = key\n53: \t}\n54: \n55: \treturn nil\n56: }\n57: \n58: func (bp *BackendPool) RemoveBackend(key string) {\n59: \tbp.mu.Lock()\n60: \tdefer bp.mu.Unlock()\n61: \n62: \tdelete(bp.backends, key)\n63: \n64: \tif bp.defaultBackend == key {\n65: \t\tbp.defaultBackend = \"\"\n66: \t\tfor k := range bp.backends {\n67: \t\t\tbp.defaultBackend = k\n68: \t\t\tbreak\n69: \t\t}\n70: \t}\n71: \n72: \tfor _, routeMap := range bp.headerRoutes {\n73: \t\tdelete(routeMap, key)\n74: \t}\n75: }\n76: \n77: func (bp *BackendPool) UpdateBackend(key, endpoint, pathPrefix string) error {\n78: \tbp.mu.Lock()\n79: \tdefer bp.mu.Unlock()\n80: \n81: \tbackend, exists := bp.backends[key]\n82: \tif !exists {\n83: \t\treturn nil\n84: \t}\n85: \n86: \tparsedURL, err := url.Parse(endpoint)\n87: \tif err != nil {\n88: \t\treturn err\n89: \t}\n90: \n91: \tbackend.URL = parsedURL\n92: \tbackend.PathPrefix = pathPrefix\n93: \n94: \treturn nil\n95: }\n96: \n97: func (bp *BackendPool) GetBackendByPath(path string) *Backend {\n98: \tbp.mu.RLock()\n99: \tdefer bp.mu.RUnlock()\n100: \n101: \tfor _, backend := range bp.backends {\n102: \t\tif backend.Healthy && len(backend.PathPrefix) > 0 &&\n103: \t\t\t(path == backend.PathPrefix ||\n104: \t\t\t\t(len(path) > len(backend.PathPrefix) && path[:len(backend.PathPrefix)] == backend.PathPrefix)) {\n105: \t\t\treturn backend\n106: \t\t}\n107: \t}\n108: \n109: \tif bp.defaultBackend != \"\" {\n110: \t\treturn bp.backends[bp.defaultBackend]\n111: \t}\n112: \n113: \treturn nil\n114: }\n115: \n116: func (bp *BackendPool) GetBackendByHeader(headerName, headerValue string) *Backend {\n117: \tbp.mu.RLock()\n118: \tdefer bp.mu.RUnlock()\n119: \n120: \trouteMap, exists := bp.headerRoutes[headerName]\n121: \tif !exists {\n122: \t\treturn nil\n123: \t}\n124: \n125: \tbackendKey, exists := routeMap[headerValue]\n126: \tif !exists {\n127: \t\treturn nil\n128: \t}\n129: \n130: \tbackend, exists := bp.backends[backendKey]\n131: \tif exists && backend.Healthy {\n132: \t\treturn backend\n133: \t}\n134: \n135: \treturn nil\n136: }\n137: \n138: func (bp *BackendPool) SetHeaderRoute(headerName, headerValue, backendKey string) {\n139: \tbp.mu.Lock()\n140: \tdefer bp.mu.Unlock()\n141: \n142: \tif _, exists := bp.backends[backendKey]; !exists {\n143: \t\treturn\n144: \t}\n145: \n146: \tif _, exists := bp.headerRoutes[headerName]; !exists {\n147: \t\tbp.headerRoutes[headerName] = make(map[string]string)\n148: \t}\n149: \n150: \tbp.headerRoutes[headerName][headerValue] = backendKey\n151: }\n152: \n153: func (bp *BackendPool) SetDefaultBackend(key string) {\n154: \tbp.mu.Lock()\n155: \tdefer bp.mu.Unlock()\n156: \n157: \tif _, exists := bp.backends[key]; exists {\n158: \t\tbp.defaultBackend = key\n159: \t}\n160: }\n161: \n162: func (bp *BackendPool) GetAllBackends() map[string]*Backend {\n163: \tbp.mu.RLock()\n164: \tdefer bp.mu.RUnlock()\n165: \n166: \tresult := make(map[string]*Backend)\n167: \tfor k, v := range bp.backends {\n168: \t\tresult[k] = v\n169: \t}\n170: \n171: \treturn result\n172: }\n173: \n174: func (b *Backend) SetHealthy(healthy bool) {\n175: \tb.mu.Lock()\n176: \tdefer b.mu.Unlock()\n177: \n178: \tb.Healthy = healthy\n179: \tif healthy {\n180: \t\tb.ConsecutiveFailures = 0\n181: \t} else {\n182: \t\tb.ConsecutiveFailures++\n183: \t}\n184: \tb.LastHealthyCheck = time.Now()\n185: }\n186: \n187: func (b *Backend) IsHealthy() bool {\n188: \tb.mu.RLock()\n189: \tdefer b.mu.RUnlock()\n190: \n191: \treturn b.Healthy\n192: }\n193: \n194: func (b *Backend) GetConsecutiveFailures() int {\n195: \tb.mu.RLock()\n196: \tdefer b.mu.RUnlock()\n197: \n198: \treturn b.ConsecutiveFailures\n199: }\n200: \n201: func (b *Backend) RecordFailure() {\n202: \tb.mu.Lock()\n203: \tdefer b.mu.Unlock()\n204: \n205: \tb.ConsecutiveFailures++\n206: \tb.Healthy = b.ConsecutiveFailures < 3\n207: }\n208: \n209: func (b *Backend) RecordSuccess() {\n210: \tb.mu.Lock()\n211: \tdefer b.mu.Unlock()\n212: \n213: \tb.ConsecutiveFailures = 0\n214: \tb.Healthy = true\n215: \tb.LastHealthyCheck = time.Now()\n216: }\n\n(End of file - total 216 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"package router\n\nimport (\n\t\"net/url\"\n\t\"sync\"\n\t\"time\"\n)\n\ntype Backend struct {\n\tURL                 *url.URL\n\tPathPrefix          string\n\tName                string\n\tHealthy             bool\n\tConsecutiveFailures int\n\tLastHealthyCheck    time.Time\n\tmu                  sync.RWMutex\n}\n\ntype BackendPool struct {\n\tbackends       map[string]*Backend","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/router/backend.go","time":{"start":1775848316321,"end":1775848316336}}}}
